    "Body": " Independent Police Monitor City of Boulder, CO - Boulder, CO Apply Now Job Details Full-time$91,000 a year Qualifications Data Analysis Skills Communication Skills Bachelor's Degree Full Job Description Description The City of Boulder is a great place to live, work, grow and play. With over 300 miles of dedicated bikeways and more than 150 miles of hiking trails, Boulder values active lifestyles and access to nature. Forty-five thousand acres of land provide open space for parks and a green belt around the city. With world class restaurants and art and music venues, The City of Boulder values diverse culture. Respect is one of our five City Values (including Customer Service, Collaboration, Integrity and Innovation) and we are committed to equity, diversity and inclusion. We celebrate and support our differences across all spectrums, including but not limited to ethnicity, gender, age, disability and sexuality. Through our focus on Racial Equity, our employee benefits, and the many programs resources we offer our staff, we continually strive to weave respect for one another into the fabric of our organization. Add your voice and talents to the City of Boulder and help us grow in service excellence for an inspired future. JOB OVERVIEW: Serving as the head of the function of Police Oversight Monitoring and Independent Review, this civilian role provides independent oversight aimed at preventing inefficient and unlawful police operations. Reporting within the City Manager's Office in partnership with the Police Chief, the Head of Independent Monitoring will establish criteria and policy around reviewing, monitoring, assisting, overseeing, and advising on the investigation of internal and citizen complaints and other administrative investigations. In addition, this role will establish program priorities and objectives and manage the implementation and evaluation of the civilian police oversight process. REPORTING STRUCTURE: (1) TITLE OF IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR: City Manager's Office Equity Program Manager (2) TITLE(S) OF POSITIONS OVER WHICH THIS POSITION HAS DIRECT SUPERVISION: May oversee or supervise administrative staff or interns. TO APPLY, PLEASE GO TO: https://thenovakconsultinggroup.recruiterbox.com/jobs/fk0q777/ (Having trouble with the link? Click Ctrl and left click) JOB DUTIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES: 1. Set the operational philosophy of the Independent Review Office and develop and maintain standard operating procedures, including protocols for handling complaints and monitoring investigations to ensure all matters are handled in a thorough, objective, fair, impartial manner. 2. Work directly with and as liaison to the police oversight panel. 3. Receive and process complaints concerning police employees; monitor the complaint investigation; and recommend best practices to the professional standards unit during the course of an investigation. 4. Perform a quality assurance function with the goal of identifying systemic changes that will improve police services to the community. These activities include: A) Independently analyzing complaint trends and recommending changes to police policy, practices and training; and B) Independently analyzing and verifying reporting trends in completed police employee disciplinary decisions. 5. Review and report trends in completed police employee disciplinary decisions. 6. Provide status reports to the police oversight panel and community and provide recommendations relevant to police policies, practices, and training to the chief of police and city manager. 7. Develop and present to the police oversight panel and city council periodic public reports describing the activities of the Auditor's Office, its findings and recommendations, the police department's response to its recommendations, and any other information pertinent to assessing the performance of the Auditor's Office. 8. Build community relationships and trust through community engagement opportunities and provide the community with any reports deemed necessary related to the work of police oversight and auditing. 9. As assigned, oversees or supervises the work of administrative staff and interns. 10. Build relationships with others and follow best practices with state and national colleagues or organizations focused on civilian oversight of police departments. 11. Recommend visionary practices that streamline and enhance civilian oversight in policing, locally and contribute to other industry leaders. MINIMUM JOB REQUIREMENTS: Bachelor's degree from an accredited college or university with major course work in criminal law, mediation, or a related field. At least seven (7) years or equivalent of experience in the field of public or private administration and supervisory responsibility or in the practice of law. No prior employment or familial relationship with the City of Boulder Police Department or individual City of Boulder Police Officers. Possess and maintain the highest degree of integrity, objectivity, and independence to ensure against any perception of bias. Demonstrated knowledge of social injustices and community attitudes towards the organization and historical and contemporary race relations. Exceptional analytical, verbal, written and people communication skills. Inclusive leadership and the ability to manage people, programs, and community boards. Experience in data analysis and trending Knowledge of police administration and organization, and the rules, laws and regulations including: Extensive experience in law enforcement Experience in police monitoring, civilian oversight administration, and procedural justice or the equivalent Demonstrated policing expertise, experience, or exposure and a knowledge of laws, principles, practice and procedures related to conducting investigations and administrative hearings State, federal, and local laws including criminal law and employment law Operations, services and activities of an oversight program Methods and techniques of investigations, training, counseling and conflict resolution Principles and practices of municipal budget preparation and administration Principles and practices of staying current with recent developments in the Police community DESIRED QUALIFICATIONS \u2013 In addition to the required minimum qualifications: Juris doctor Bilingual in Spanish "
